<%= stream_react_component("ReactIntlRSCDemo",
                           props: { userName: "Abanoub", cartItems: 5, productPrice: 1234.56 },
                           prerender: true,
                           trace: true,
                           id: "ReactIntlRSCDemo-react-component-0") %>

<hr/>

<h2>Switch locale</h2>
<p>
  <%= link_to "English", react_intl_rsc_demo_path(locale: "en") %> |
  <%= link_to "Français", react_intl_rsc_demo_path(locale: "fr") %> |
  <%= link_to "العربية", react_intl_rsc_demo_path(locale: "ar") %>
</p>
<p>
  The locale switch triggers a full page reload. Server Components render on the server,
  so the new locale has to travel from Rails → <code>railsContext.i18nLocale</code> →
  the render function, and the Server Component tree is re-serialized in the new language.
  There is no way to switch locales on the client for Server Component content without a
  server roundtrip.
</p>

<hr/>

<h2>About this example</h2>
<p>
  This page demonstrates using <code>react-intl</code>'s formatter inside a React Server
  Component. Because Server Components can't use React hooks or Context, the usual
  <code>useIntl()</code> / <code>&lt;IntlProvider&gt;</code> API is unavailable. The workaround
  shown here uses:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>The render function pattern.</strong> The Server Component is registered as a
    2-argument function <code>(props, railsContext) =&gt; () =&gt; JSX</code>. React on Rails
    detects 2+ arguments and treats the function as a <em>render function</em>, passing
    <code>railsContext</code> (which carries <code>i18nLocale</code>) as the second argument.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong><code>createIntl</code> from <code>@formatjs/intl</code>.</strong> This is the
    non-React core of <code>react-intl</code>. It returns the same <code>intl</code> object
    you'd get from <code>useIntl()</code>, without needing React Context. All formatting
    (interpolation, pluralization, numbers, dates) works.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Locale from Rails.</strong> The controller has
    <code>before_action :set_demo_locale</code> that reads <code>params[:locale]</code> and
    sets <code>I18n.locale</code>. That flows into <code>railsContext.i18nLocale</code>
    automatically via <code>ReactOnRails::Helper#rails_context</code>.
  </li>
</ol>

<h3>Why this is a workaround, not the ideal solution</h3>
<ul>
  <li>
    Only the <strong>top-level registered</strong> Server Component receives
    <code>railsContext</code>. Nested Server Components would need <code>intl</code> or
    <code>locale</code> passed as a prop (prop drilling).
  </li>
  <li>
    The render function convention (returning a component function instead of JSX) is a
    React on Rails convention, not standard React.
  </li>
  <li>
    Translations are hard-coded inline in the component for this demo. In a real app you'd
    run <code>ReactOnRails::Locales.compile</code> to generate <code>translations.json</code>
    from your Rails YAML locale files and import it.
  </li>
</ul>

<h3>The eventual fix</h3>
<p>
  Issue <%= link_to "shakacode/react_on_rails#3081", "https://github.com/shakacode/react_on_rails/issues/3081" %>
  tracks adding an AsyncLocalStorage-based request store to React on Rails. Once that ships,
  any Server Component anywhere in the tree will be able to call a framework-provided helper
  like <code>getLocale()</code> or <code>getTranslations()</code> without being a render function
  and without prop drilling — matching the developer experience of Next.js's <code>next-intl</code>.
</p>

<h3>Setup required</h3>
<p>
  This demo requires the <code>@formatjs/intl</code> package (the non-React core of
  <code>react-intl</code>). If you're seeing a missing-module error, install it and rebuild
  the bundles:
</p>
<pre><code>cd react_on_rails_pro/spec/dummy
pnpm install
pnpm run build:dev</code></pre>

<h3>Relevant files</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code>client/app/ror-auto-load-components/ReactIntlRSCDemo.jsx</code> — the Server Component</li>
  <li><code>app/controllers/pages_controller.rb</code> — <code>react_intl_rsc_demo</code> action + <code>set_demo_locale</code></li>
  <li><code>app/views/pages/react_intl_rsc_demo.html.erb</code> — this view</li>
  <li><code>config/routes.rb</code> — the route</li>
</ul>
